caption: Started with Toro tartar and seared scallops, must get! Would skip the grilled octopus / octopus in general, other fish cuts are better. Their specialty Nigri was worth it, definitely recommend both of the signature smoked, Juno king/queen, a few of the specialty Nigri (hotate and zuke sake) with the eel and tuna trios. The strawberry covered chocolate truffles were also very good!

This is one of the best sushi restaurants I've been to in Chicago. You won't regret paying for the experience. MUST get the Juno King! If you're looking for Michelin Star food and super delicate japanese sushi, this is your place. Taste and quality is above the mainstream sushi places. The cocktails are just as good. In a taste test, I tried this among several other well known and well respected sushi purveyors. In that test you have the ability to notice subtle differences, even in the quality and cook of the rice. You notice the balance and ratios of differing ingredients, do they blend well, is something too overpowering. This was unanimously the most well received. You could pick any roll and it would taste amazing. The homemade soy sauce is unbelievable. Every roll we got was immediately recognizable as of higher quality and structure. Not too much rice or anything, you could say the rolls were “perfectly balanced, as all things should be.” A clear winner in the Chicago sushi taste test among many of my sushi loving friends and family.

Not the best but on par with the rest of service at a minimum. The sake that was recommended to us was surprisingly light, and we enjoyed it thoroughly.  My only quip was about the size of the tables. For how sushi is presented, with drinks, water, and etc, table ends up very crowded. The kitchen does spread your food out, but nonetheless it's a little tight.  Overall, one of the best dinner experiences we've had in the city.

I’ve been to Juno on a few different occasions over the years while in Chicago for business.  Always make a reservation!!  Weekends are busy, be prepared for a wait during peak times. It is a small restaurant and small staff.  If you want an Omakase you MUST call and book it in advance. It cannot be booked online. I absolutely reccomend trying it if you can.  There is a front room (with a bar by the door, quieter) and a back room (with a sushi bar, main dining area ). You can never know where you’ll be placed unless you call and ask. If it’s important to you to be seated in the back then you must make a reservation early, and call to confirm the seating area.  I won’t deny it’s expensive and portions are small, but ingredients are top notch and very fresh. The cuts of fish aren’t oversized and thick like most bargain sushi places. Their selection is very traditional sushi with a modern flair. If you want a California roll don’t come here.  All that being said; the best time to go is probably on a Thursday night. I reccomend trying the uni shooters, smoked hamachi, seared scallop pasta dish, and any of the nigiri samplers they have. Drink sake. Any sake. Amazing.  Thanks!

This was a saddening experience. When you want sushi, you want one of two things: cheap massive quantities of fish and rice or a culinary explosion of wonders in your mouth that leaves your tongue as satisfied as your stomach. This place, strangely, was neither.  The ambience was loud--despite the barely audible music, sound carried too well, and despite the few diners, it was not the setting I would expect or want for the price or attitude. Otherwise, the interior design was a fresh taste from the red and black color scheme seen at most sushi/Japanese restaurants.  The service was slow. Our waiter walked like a muted robot, and an older Japanese lady (the host? owner/owner's wife?) walked at about half a mile an hour and would hovered near your table before swooping in to take that empty juice glass. I could tell she was zeroing in on our table well before she actually stepped forth into official presence. That bit was odd. But beyond these petty observations, the service was simply slow. We ordered two sakes, which for some reason took 5-10 minutes to arrive, then when we finished those and ordered another two, it took again about 10 minutes for the new glasses to arrive. We ordered appetizers--basic stuff, nothing complicated--and waited 10-20 minutes for the first to arrive. By the time both arrived we ordered the main sushi dinners. Our waiter said the sashimi chef's choice ($42) was enough for two people: my cousin finished it in two minutes, not nearly satisfied. Of course, with 5+ sushi chefs working behind me, each sushi dinner we ordered took between 10 and 20 minutes to reach our table. We ordered a plate of nigiri/sashimi each, then maybe four extra rolls totalling $270, and were never full. Partly, I think, because they decided we needed to wait 20+ minutes between each minuscule course. I considered, upon leaving, finding a cheap sushi place to fill up on. We spent maybe two hours there and were wholly unsatisfied.  The food, at this point an afterthought, was okay. It was not worth the price, but it had highlights. Skip the chef's choice nigir/sashimi dishes ($40, $42 respectively). They were uninteresting and unfulfilling for the price (wasabi seemed a little overbearing in the nigir for a couple of the fish as well). A few Maki rolls were delicious and definitely worth the price, but with the quantity balanced against the massive wait, it wasn't worth it.  If you, like me, miss Katsu's and are looking for a replacement, this isn't it. Though, if their service sped up (like 2-3 times as fast) and the price lowers a couple bucks, it might be worth revisiting.
